this is the newest full-length lp from
rapper and songwriter saba it's been
four years since the drop of the fan
favorite care for me in 2018 a record i
had a difficult time getting into
despite its many conceptual and
narrative bars because at least in my
opinion saba's flows and production
choices came off a little too amateurish
to hold a candle to his brainy hip-hop
contemporaries that were obviously
influencing this record and i would say
that's still the case for a few good
things but the quality gap this time
around is a lot narrower there are some
noticeable cracks here and there in the
track list i picked up on right away
like the opening track free samples
whose gentle strings and bass arpeggios
sound a little bit like something off of
kendrick's tpap saba's slowly
intensifying flow later into the track
doesn't make the connection any less
obvious then there are shaftly starting
vocal lines that take up the whole first
leg of the track some of which are
obviously off-key it's not the best
first impression for your entire record
meanwhile fearmonger has a solid groove
and some unique vocal inflections on the
flow side which go off the rails around
the hook sounding like chance the rapper
trying to do a bad impression of the
most eccentric outcast chorus ever then
there's a simpler time which is
instrumentally a complete mess just
directionless neo-soul vocal licks and
badly mixed wraps sitting on top of what
sounds like a metronome a cuckoo clock
and a typewriter in a knife fight i hear
the off kilter style this b is going for
but there's a very very very thin line
between this kind of instrumental
sounding like clutter and sounding
together and i think that line has been
crossed that being said though i think
few good things has a few good things on
it some thoughtful smooth and meditative
highlights to offer tracks that may fall
on deaf ears if you're looking for
something more aggressive explosive
louder bolder lord knows that's where my
mind is at most of the time but i can't
deny there's something to the low-key
groovy pop rap of one way the chorus on
this one repeats like a dream you keep
having over and over there's something
about the instrumental that sounds like
a warm fuzzy memory from the 90s
meanwhile saba's bars indulge in this
luxury fantasy that his recent success
has afforded him which feels especially
surreal as he juxtaposes that against
the financial struggles that he grew up
with there's then the slick mesmerizing
and speedy flows packed into every
corner of come my way which features
crazy bone i think you don't really need
to know too much more than that to
understand the kind of legacy of the
torch that saba is carrying
stylistically on this track lyrically
saba is daydreaming about making money
on this one it's essentially this
record's first of the month still with
smino and black may be the most
mesmerizing track on the entire lp but
it's not all vibes saba throws a banger
into the mix right off the bat with the
song survivor's guilt featuring g-herbo
and saba doesn't hesitate to very
aggressively dive into the emotions he's
been wrestling with since making it out
of the poverty he was born into with
understandably bitter portrayals of
street violence and food deserts the
somewhat mystical trap beat on this one
works really well with the fiery gang
choruses but then again there are
moments on this thing that remind me a
little bit of care for me in that they
don't go far enough or they deliver a
really strong core concept idea but they
aren't wrapped in a super definitive
song or sound the track soldier for
example features this kendrick chorus
matched with beats and flows that sound
like they could have been lifted off of
outcasts atlan's but still the opening
verse on this track about saba becoming
a father is one of the best this record
has to offer the production on if i had
a dollar is a little one-dimensional
with its woozy keys and dry trap beats
but i do love the song sentiment about
winning failing growing progressing not
to mention saba's sung chorus on the
track is
way better than i would have expected
stop it please continues the record's
narrative of wrestling with success to

little then we have the massive title
